// The pool of "Dear Crisis, ___" conversation starters.
// `text` is the part AFTER "Dear Crisis," — display and copy prepend the framing.
// Shape: a grounded insight/factoid, a beat, then a personal question that turns
// the reader inward. Add or cut freely; each needs a stable, unique `id`.

export type Topic = "nature" | "systems" | "spirit" | "mind" | "work" | "myth";
export type Mood = "wry" | "tender" | "provocative" | "awe";

export type Line = {
  id: string;
  text: string;
  topics: Topic[];
  moods: Mood[];
};

type RawLine = { id: string; text: string };

const rawLines: RawLine[] = [
  { id: "1", text: "a brainless slime mold redesigned the Tokyo rail network in a weekend. I've been “getting around to” reorganizing one closet since 2023. What's the system in your life a blob would've fixed by now?" },
  { id: "2", text: "the wolves repaired an entire river by eating elk — no summit, no steering committee. What's the elk in your life you keep scheduling meetings about instead of just eating?" },
  { id: "3", text: "trees quietly pump sugar underground to feed each other's dying seedlings, ad-free, better uptime than the internet. Who's a seedling you could slip a little sugar to this week?" },
  { id: "4", text: "we say “it” about the river so we never owe it a birthday card. What would you actually treat differently tomorrow if you called it “kin”?" },
  { id: "5", text: "an old-growth forest's proudest move is that it stopped growing outward and started growing deep. Where are you overdue to do the same — and what are you scared you'd lose?" },
  { id: "6", text: "everyone recycles harder while Moloch quietly laughs. Be honest: what do you do mostly to feel less guilty, that mainly just… helps you feel less guilty?" },
  { id: "7", text: "we built the machines to free us from the treadmill, then handed the treadmill a motor. What's your one “time-saving” thing that somehow devours the most time?" },
  { id: "8", text: "a compost heap turns every ending into next spring's soil; our economy never learned to rot. What ending are you composting — and what are you just calling “away”?" },
  { id: "9", text: "a starling tracks only its seven nearest neighbors, and a thousand of them dodge the hawk as one. Who are your seven — and when did you last actually watch them?" },
  { id: "10", text: "they keep insisting the times are too urgent to slow down. So where, exactly, are you moving fast mainly to avoid feeling something?" },
  { id: "11", text: "the “self-made” man turns out to be a lichen who forgot he's half algae. Who's the algae quietly keeping you alive that you've stopped thanking?" },
  { id: "12", text: "we swim in cheap energy like a fish swims in water — invisible until it's gone. What else are you not seeing in your life right now… precisely because it's everywhere?" },
  { id: "13", text: "growth purely for its own sake is, medically speaking, the thing a tumor does. Where are you growing something only because stopping would feel like failing?" },
  { id: "14", text: "the largest living thing on Earth is a shy Oregon fungus, thousands of years old, no CEO, no quarterly report. What would you build if nothing had to show results this quarter?" },
  { id: "15", text: "you're a hyperobject — too vast to see, yet in every weather report and grocery bill. What “someday” problem have you filed under future precisely because it's already here?" },
  { id: "16", text: "the most connected humans in history are also the loneliest; somewhere the two graphs crossed. Honestly — how many of your connections would notice if you went quiet for a week?" },
  { id: "17", text: "nobody is actually driving the superorganism: not the billionaires, not the voters, not the presidents. So who have you been blaming for something no single hand is steering?" },
  { id: "18", text: "a monoculture is gloriously efficient right up until the weather turns. Which part of your life is one bad season away from finding that out?" },
  { id: "19", text: "in Potawatomi the same root word means “berry” and “gift.” What would you receive differently tomorrow if the harvest were a present, not an inventory?" },
  { id: "20", text: "despair, it turns out, is just hope that hasn't been composted yet. What are you refusing to let rot so something new can finally grow?" },
  { id: "21", text: "we spent ten thousand years unlearning how to hear the world speak, then hired therapists so we'd feel less alone. When did you last let the more-than-human world get a word in?" },
  { id: "22", text: "there's a homesickness you can feel without ever leaving home. If grief is just love with nowhere to sit down — where will you let yours sit tonight?" },
  { id: "23", text: "we've somehow turned “solving the crisis” into a growth industry. Where in your life are you impressively, exhaustingly busy in precisely the wrong direction?" },
  { id: "24", text: "modernity may be one half of a brain that fired the half that saw things whole. What have you optimized so hard you forgot why you wanted it?" },
  { id: "25", text: "a seed's real genius is knowing when not to sprout. What are you forcing to grow that's quietly begging you for a winter?" },
  { id: "26", text: "infinite growth on a finite planet — an alien economist would assume we were doing satire. What would you have to keep believing for your busiest day to make sense?" },
  { id: "27", text: "you're standing in the doorway between an old story and one not yet born. What are you doing in the doorway — panicking, scrolling, or paying attention?" },
  { id: "28", text: "a river “wastes” miles meandering, and that laziness is exactly what stops it flooding. What meander in your life do you keep trying to straighten into a to-do list?" },
  { id: "29", text: "a forest banks diversity for the bad year the way we're supposed to keep savings. What did you cash in for one more productive quarter that you'd secretly like back?" },
  { id: "30", text: "you don't want my panic and you don't want my optimism. You want my attention. Okay — you've got it. Now what do I actually want to do about you?" },
  { id: "31", text: "there's an old Cree word — wetiko — for the hunger that consumes without limit and convinces the host it's perfectly fine. Where does yours whisper “just one more” the loudest… and do you still believe it?" },
  { id: "32", text: "a tree hands the fungus 30% of its sugar for minerals it could never reach alone, and calls it a fair deal. What “tax” in your life is secretly the best trade you make?" },
  { id: "33", text: "the part of the mind that measures and controls was only ever meant to serve the part that sees things whole — and somewhere it seized the house. Which one's been running your calendar this week?" },
  { id: "34", text: "someone once said the opposite of a trap is a garden. What have you been guarding like a trap… that might actually grow if you treated it like a garden?" },
  { id: "35", text: "a gift loses value the instant you hoard it and multiplies the moment you pass it on — the exact inverse of money. What are you stockpiling that only comes alive when it moves?" },
  { id: "36", text: "the old animists swore the land looks back at you. Faintly unsettling. When did you last stand somewhere long enough to be looked at?" },
  { id: "37", text: "turns out hope isn't a mood you wait around for — it's a thing you do, like push-ups. What's one rep you could manage today?" },
  { id: "38", text: "humanity now wields godlike technology with roughly the self-governance of a group chat at 2am. Where has your power quietly outrun your wisdom lately?" },
  { id: "39", text: "there's a name floated for the age after this one — the Symbiocene, where we live with instead of off. What's one relationship you'd move from “off” to “with”?" },
  { id: "40", text: "there's a ritual where people speak as the river, the wolf, the last bee, just to escape their own skull for an hour. If a creature could send you a “Dear Human” letter — who'd write, and what would it say?" },
  { id: "41", text: "the Buddha basically did degrowth 2,500 years ago and called it enlightenment: whatever you tie down comes loose, whatever you build up falls. What are you clutching that might feel lighter held loosely?" },
  { id: "42", text: "the doomers call hope a drug; the hopeful call doom a cop-out; both are sometimes right. Which one are you reaching for today to avoid simply… looking?" },
  { id: "43", text: "every solution ships with a second-order effect nobody printed on the label. What “fix” in your life quietly became next year's problem?" },
  { id: "44", text: "when one starling turns, the whole flock feels it before it makes any sense to. Whose small turn are you waiting on for permission — or are you the one meant to turn first?" },
  { id: "45", text: "pull a single keystone species and the whole arch of an ecosystem quietly collapses. Who's the keystone in your life you've been treating like they're optional?" },
  { id: "46", text: "our kind of money literally has to grow or it dies — which makes it brilliant at whispering there's never enough. Where does “not enough” run your decisions when it isn't even true?" },
  { id: "47", text: "the coming years may simply hold less more — less stuff, less speed, less scale. If “more” quietly moved out, what would you be relieved to stop carrying?" },
  { id: "48", text: "the frog never jumps, because the water heats one polite degree at a time. What's been warming so slowly around you that you've stopped feeling the temperature?" },
  { id: "49", text: "one story says you're a separate self adrift in a world of strangers; the other says you exist because everything else does. Which story did you wake up inside of this morning?" },
  { id: "50", text: "Bayo says a crisis is a place where “a composting of ourselves can take place” — delightfully gross. What part of who you used to be is finally ready to become soil?" },
  { id: "51", text: "in an economy engineered to harvest your attention, spending it on purpose is nearly an act of rebellion. What's deserved an hour of yours for months and still isn't getting it?" },
  { id: "52", text: "the dreamers keep sketching “omni-win” — a game where your winning doesn't require anyone's losing. When did you last win something where nobody had to lose?" },
  { id: "53", text: "a beaver doesn't attend a single meeting about watershed management; it just builds the dam and the wetland shows up. What would you build this week if you stopped waiting for the meeting?" },
  { id: "54", text: "coral reefs — the most crowded, dazzling cities in the ocean — are built by animals softer than jelly, one tiny skeleton at a time. What are you leaving that's small now but might outlast you?" },
  { id: "55", text: "a single teaspoon of healthy soil holds more living creatures than there are humans on Earth. When did you last treat the ground under you as more alive than the phone in your hand?" },
  { id: "56", text: "Darwin's final book wasn't about finches — it was about earthworms quietly turning the whole planet's soil, unthanked, for millions of years. Who's doing the quiet, unglamorous work in your life that you've never actually thanked?" },
  { id: "57", text: "dung beetles navigate by the light of the Milky Way. You have the entire galaxy for a compass — what have you been steering by instead?" },
  { id: "58", text: "salmon swim upstream to die, and their bodies feed the forest so trees miles from the sea are built partly from ocean. What are you willing to spend yourself completely on?" },
  { id: "59", text: "no single monarch butterfly survives the whole migration; it takes four generations to make the round trip. What are you working on that you'll never personally see finished — and is that okay with you?" },
  { id: "60", text: "octopuses think with their arms — most of their neurons aren't in their head at all. Where in your life has your body known the answer long before your head caught up?" },
  { id: "61", text: "leafcutter ants were farming fungus fifty million years before humans planted a single seed. What are you certain you invented that something older already knew?" },
  { id: "62", text: "bees decide where to build a new home by a kind of dance-off — a genuine, patient democracy with no king. When did your certainty last lose gracefully to a better idea?" },
  { id: "63", text: "redwoods have shockingly shallow roots; they stay standing only because they interlock with their neighbors underground. Whose roots are you tangled with — and have you been pretending you stand alone?" },
  { id: "64", text: "Pando is a forest of 47,000 aspen trunks that is secretly one single organism sharing one root system. Where do you draw the line around “you,” and is the line even real?" },
  { id: "65", text: "bamboo can spend years growing nothing you can see, all roots, then shoot up ninety feet in a season. What in your life is in its invisible-root phase, and can you resist yanking it up to check?" },
  { id: "66", text: "a nurse log — a fallen, rotting tree — becomes the nursery for the next generation of the forest. What ending in your life are you standing on top of without realizing it's feeding you?" },
  { id: "67", text: "some pinecones only open in the heat of a wildfire; the seed waits its whole life for the thing that looks like the end. What if the fire you're dreading is the only thing that opens you?" },
  { id: "68", text: "sea otters keep the kelp forests alive by eating the urchins that would eat them; remove one furry animal and the whole underwater forest vanishes. What small thing are you tempted to cut that's quietly holding everything up?" },
  { id: "69", text: "moss has no roots and no plumbing, yet it holds water for a whole hillside and asks for almost nothing. What would “traveling light” actually look like for you?" },
  { id: "70", text: "mitochondria — the batteries in every one of your cells — were once free-living bacteria that moved in and never left. You are, quite literally, a collaboration. Who are you still pretending you don't need?" },
  { id: "71", text: "you have more bacterial cells riding along in you than human ones; “yourself” is mostly a democracy of strangers. So who exactly is the “I” making your New Year's resolutions?" },
  { id: "72", text: "a forest under attack sends chemical warnings on the wind so its neighbors can raise their defenses before the bugs arrive. When did you last warn someone, or let yourself be warned, before it was too late?" },
  { id: "73", text: "the oldest, biggest “mother trees” funnel extra carbon to the smallest seedlings in the shade. Who mothered you into existence that you've stopped sending anything back to?" },
  { id: "74", text: "phytoplankton too small to see make roughly half the oxygen you'll breathe today. Every second breath is a gift from something you'll never meet — how does that change the breath you're taking right now?" },
  { id: "75", text: "when a whale dies and sinks, its body feeds a whole ecosystem on the seafloor for decades. Even our endings could be that generous — what do you want yours to feed?" },
  { id: "76", text: "mangroves stand in the surf and take the punch of the storm so the village behind them survives. Who's been the mangrove for you — and who are you standing in front of?" },
  { id: "77", text: "a wetland is basically a planet's kidney, quietly filtering poison into clean water. What's the unglamorous thing in your life doing the filtering you never notice until it's paved over?" },
  { id: "78", text: "spider silk is, ounce for ounce, tougher than steel, and a spider makes it from bugs and patience. What are you convinced you need money or permission for that you could actually make from what's already around you?" },
  { id: "79", text: "life has been running R&D for 3.8 billion years and its one design rule is: create the conditions for more life. By that measure, is what you're building today alive — or just busy?" },
  { id: "80", text: "octopuses taste with their skin and see with their whole body; we narrowed the world to five official senses and called it objectivity. What are you refusing to know because it didn't come through an approved channel?" },
  { id: "81", text: "Moloch is the old name for the god you sacrifice what you love to, just to stay competitive. What have you already fed him this week without noticing it was an offering?" },
  { id: "82", text: "the Red Queen told Alice you have to run as fast as you can just to stay in the same place. What race are you sprinting in that you never actually agreed to enter?" },
  { id: "83", text: "an economy counts a car crash as growth and a standing forest as nothing. What are you measuring in your own life that rewards the wrong thing entirely?" },
  { id: "84", text: "Goodhart's law: the moment a measure becomes a target, it stops measuring anything real. Which number in your life did you start gaming the day you started chasing it?" },
  { id: "85", text: "make an engine more efficient and people just use more of it — that's Jevons' paradox, two centuries old. Where has “saving time” only bought you more to do?" },
  { id: "86", text: "your brain values a reward now far more than a bigger one later; evolution built you to raid the fridge, not to plan for 2070. Knowing that, what future are you quietly robbing to pay for tonight?" },
  { id: "87", text: "every price tag hides the costs quietly dumped on someone downstream, or downwind, or not born yet. What's cheap in your life only because someone else is paying for it out of sight?" },
  { id: "88", text: "Elinor Ostrom won a Nobel for proving ordinary people can govern a shared resource without a boss or a market — they just have to talk and trust. What commons in your life is dying only because nobody started the conversation?" },
  { id: "89", text: "reindeer dropped on an island with no predators bred to 6,000, ate everything, and crashed to 42 in one winter. What are you growing right now with the brakes deliberately disconnected?" },
  { id: "90", text: "complex societies collapse, Tainter argued, not from one disaster but because each new fix costs more and returns less. Where are you adding complexity to your life and calling it progress?" },
  { id: "91", text: "humanity is starting to look like a single blind, hungry amoeba optimizing for more throughput, no steering wheel, nobody home. In your own small orbit, who's actually driving — or are you also just flowing toward the food?" },
  { id: "92", text: "a boiling frog never jumps because the water heats one gentle degree at a time. Forget the frog for a second — what's your water temperature right now, honestly?" },
  { id: "93", text: "we mostly search for answers where the light is good, not where we dropped the keys. What problem are you solving because it's easy, while the real one sits in the dark?" },
  { id: "94", text: "Cassandra could see exactly what was coming and was cursed so no one would believe her. Whose warning in your life have you been treating as background noise?" },
  { id: "95", text: "the attention economy doesn't sell you anything — you're the thing being sold, by the hour, to the highest bidder. Who profited from the last two hours of your one finite life?" },
  { id: "96", text: "outrage travels faster and farther online than joy, so the machine feeds you rage because rage pays. When did a feeling you had last actually belong to you, and not to an algorithm's quarterly targets?" },
  { id: "97", text: "a song doesn't get smaller when a million people sing it — some goods multiply by sharing, the exact opposite of gold. What are you hoarding that would only grow if you gave it away?" },
  { id: "98", text: "Chesterton said don't tear down a fence until you know why it was built. What tradition or rule are you itching to bulldoze without first asking what it was quietly holding back?" },
  { id: "99", text: "impermanence isn't the bad news; it's the only reason anything blooms at all. What are you gripping so hard that you're strangling the very thing you love about it?" },
  { id: "100", text: "the Tao says the softest thing in the world, water, wears down the hardest. Where have you been trying to be the rock when the water was winning all along?" },
  { id: "101", text: "wu wei — effortless action — is doing by not forcing, like a sail using a wind it didn't make. What in your life are you rowing against that you could just… let carry you?" },
  { id: "102", text: "kintsugi mends broken pottery with gold, so the cracks become the most beautiful part. Which of your breaks are you still hiding that might be the most golden thing about you?" },
  { id: "103", text: "the Japanese practice “forest bathing” — no hiking, no goal, just standing among trees and letting them work on you. When did you last be somewhere green with absolutely nothing to achieve?" },
  { id: "104", text: "wabi-sabi finds the beauty precisely in the weathered, the imperfect, the passing. What are you rejecting in yourself for the crime of not being finished or flawless?" },
  { id: "105", text: "many cultures kept a Sabbath — one day where making and buying simply stopped, by sacred law. In a life with no off-switch, what would you protect if resting were holy instead of lazy?" },
  { id: "106", text: "memento mori: monks kept a skull on the desk not to be morbid, but to remember the clock is running. If you truly felt the shortness of it today, what would you stop pretending you have time for?" },
  { id: "107", text: "the Haudenosaunee weigh big decisions against their effect seven generations out. If you had to answer to your great-great-grandchildren for today's choices, which one would you change first?" },
  { id: "108", text: "there's a clock being built to tick once a year for 10,000 years, just to stretch how far we're willing to care. How far into the future does your imagination actually reach before it goes blank — and why there?" },
  { id: "109", text: "astronauts who see the whole Earth at once often come back changed, borders erased, weirdly tender. You don't have a rocket — but what would it take to see your life from that far up?" },
  { id: "110", text: "researchers find that awe literally shrinks the sense of self and makes people kinder. When did you last let yourself be that small on purpose?" },
  { id: "111", text: "Mary Oliver asked what you plan to do with your one wild and precious life. Not your career, not your five-year plan — your one wild life. Well?" },
  { id: "112", text: "Indra's net is a web where every jewel reflects every other jewel, endlessly. Who are you reflecting today without knowing it, and who's reflecting you?" },
  { id: "113", text: "ubuntu says: I am because we are. How much of who you're proud of was actually smuggled in by other people?" },
  { id: "114", text: "Rilke told a young poet to be patient with everything unsolved and to live the questions themselves. Which question in your life have you been trying to kill with an answer just to stop the discomfort?" },
  { id: "115", text: "Thich Nhat Hanh saw the cloud, the rain, the sun, and the logger's breakfast all inside a single sheet of paper. Pick one ordinary thing near you — who and what is secretly inside it?" },
  { id: "116", text: "the Stoics said suffering comes from confusing what we control with what we don't. What are you exhausting yourself trying to control that was never yours to hold?" },
  { id: "117", text: "amor fati — to not just accept your fate but to love it. What's the one thing about your life right now you'd have to stop resisting for that to even be thinkable?" },
  { id: "118", text: "Rumi said to welcome each emotion like a guest, even grief, even shame, because each was sent as a guide. Which feeling have you been leaving out on the porch, and what might it be trying to tell you?" },
  { id: "119", text: "the “second arrow” in Buddhism is the suffering you add to pain by rejecting it. Where are you shooting yourself with the second arrow right now?" },
  { id: "120", text: "Robin Wall Kimmerer calls it the honorable harvest: never take more than you need, never take the first or the last. Where in your life would “enough” feel like loss — and what if it were freedom?" },
  { id: "121", text: "a gift creates a bond; a purchase ends one the moment the receipt prints. What relationship in your life would change if you stopped keeping score of who owes whom?" },
  { id: "122", text: "Joanna Macy insisted we honor our pain for the world instead of numbing it, because the pain is proof we're still connected. What ache have you been medicating that might actually be love with nowhere to go?" },
  { id: "123", text: "deep ecology invites you to widen the self until defending a river feels like defending your own body. What would you protect fiercely if you truly felt it was part of you?" },
  { id: "124", text: "Bayo Akomolafe says we won't arrive intact, and maybe that was never the point. What are you clinging to arriving as, when the journey is clearly here to remake you?" },
  { id: "125", text: "the “space between stories” is that vertigo when the old life is over but the new one hasn't started. If you're in that doorway right now, what are you doing there besides refreshing your phone?" },
  { id: "126", text: "the overview effect, kintsugi, forest bathing — every culture keeps reinventing “slow down and look.” Why does it keep taking a crisis to make you do the simplest possible thing?" },
  { id: "127", text: "an ecosystem's genius is redundancy — three species doing a similar job so losing one isn't fatal. Where have you “streamlined” your life so hard that one bad day could take it all down?" },
  { id: "128", text: "a prairie's real life is underground, roots plunging fifteen feet where the lawn's go two inches. Which are you tending lately — the visible green, or the deep root nobody claps for?" },
  { id: "129", text: "termites build mounds that hold a perfect temperature with no electricity, and we're only now copying them for our buildings. What obvious wisdom is right in front of you, disguised as “just nature”?" },
  { id: "130", text: "a river straightened for efficiency floods catastrophically; its lazy meanders were the safety feature all along. What detour in your life were you built to take that you keep trying to optimize away?" },
  { id: "131", text: "Suzanne Simard proved trees don't just compete — they feed rivals, warn strangers, and keep dying stumps alive for decades. What if the story that it's all competition was the fairy tale?" },
  { id: "132", text: "degrowth isn't poverty; it's the radical idea that maybe we already have enough and the problem is how it's shared. What would “enough” actually feel like in your body, and when did you last feel it?" },
  { id: "133", text: "the hedonic treadmill resets your happiness back to baseline no matter what you buy or achieve. Knowing the treadmill never ends, what would you step off of today?" },
  { id: "134", text: "planned obsolescence means things are designed to die so you'll buy them again. What in your life was built to break that you've been blaming yourself for not keeping alive?" },
  { id: "135", text: "a cleaner fish swims straight into a predator's mouth and comes out alive, because the whole reef runs on a trust older than teeth. Where is your life quietly held together by a trust you never signed?" },
  { id: "136", text: "Tainter said societies fall when the cost of holding it all together finally outruns the benefit. What are you spending most of your energy just holding together — and is it still worth it?" },
  { id: "137", text: "Ostrom's commoners succeeded by making the rules together and watching out for each other, not by being policed. What in your life is falling apart only for lack of a shared agreement nobody's dared propose?" },
  { id: "138", text: "the “tragedy of the commons” is really a tragedy of no conversation; a talking village keeps its field alive. Which of your shared spaces is dying in polite silence?" },
  { id: "139", text: "a keystone isn't the biggest stone in the arch — it's the one that, pulled, brings the whole thing down. Who in your life is doing keystone work while getting bystander credit?" },
  { id: "140", text: "we call the more-than-human world “resources” and “ecosystem services,” as if the sea were an employee. What changes in you the moment the world stops being staff and starts being kin?" },
  { id: "141", text: "David Abram asks how we ever stopped feeling the land looking back at us. Go outside tonight and let something look at you — what happens?" },
  { id: "142", text: "animist cultures never had to be told the river was alive; that was the default, and forgetting it was the anomaly. What did you have to be taught to stop feeling?" },
  { id: "143", text: "solastalgia is the grief of watching a place you love change while you're still standing in it. Where are you homesick without having gone anywhere?" },
  { id: "144", text: "Glenn Albrecht wants to name the next age the Symbiocene — an era defined by living with instead of off. What's one relationship in your life you could move from extracting to accompanying?" },
  { id: "145", text: "Charles Eisenstein says our whole civilization runs on a story that you're a separate self in a dead universe. What would you do differently for one hour if that story simply weren't true?" },
  { id: "146", text: "the Buddha basically prescribed enough-ness 2,500 years ago and called the endless wanting the root of suffering. What wanting have you mistaken for a personality trait?" },
  { id: "147", text: "the Stoics practiced the “view from above,” imagining their whole life seen from the stars, to right-size their panic. Zoom out on today's biggest worry — how big is it from up there?" },
  { id: "148", text: "Keats praised “negative capability” — the strength to stay in doubt and mystery without lunging for a tidy answer. Where are you lunging for certainty just to escape the discomfort of not knowing?" },
  { id: "149", text: "a good ancestor, Roman Krznaric says, plants trees whose shade they'll never sit in. What are you planting that isn't for you?" },
  { id: "150", text: "the desert monks fled to the wilderness because they suspected the crowd was making everyone a little insane. What would go quiet in you if you left the crowd for even a day?" },
  { id: "151", text: "tardigrades can survive being boiled, frozen, dried to dust, and shot into the vacuum of space. What have you survived that you still talk about like it broke you?" },
  { id: "152", text: "a fig and its wasp are so entangled that neither can reproduce without the other — tens of millions of years of showing up. What relationship in your life is that load-bearing, and when did you last tend it?" },
  { id: "153", text: "a locust is a shy, solitary grasshopper until crowding flips a switch and it becomes a swarm. What conditions turn you into the worst version of yourself, and can you see them coming?" },
  { id: "154", text: "some cicadas stay underground for exactly 13 or 17 years — prime numbers, to dodge predators — then emerge all at once. What have you been underground on, and how will you know it's time?" },
  { id: "155", text: "cyanobacteria once “polluted” the whole planet with a toxic gas called oxygen, and that catastrophe became the air you breathe. What disaster in your past turned out to be the thing you now run on?" },
  { id: "156", text: "you're made of carbon forged inside dying stars; you are, factually, the universe briefly walking around. Given that, what would embarrass a star about how you spent today?" },
  { id: "157", text: "Lynn Margulis showed the biggest leaps in evolution came not from competition but from former enemies merging into one being. Who could you stop fighting long enough to become something new with?" },
  { id: "158", text: "Kropotkin watched Siberian animals survive brutal winters by cooperating, and asked why we only tell the tooth-and-claw story. Whose survival are you quietly holding up, and who's holding up yours?" },
  { id: "159", text: "crows make tools, hold grudges, and teach their kids your face; intelligence didn't wait for us. What are you sure only humans can do that you've simply never watched closely enough?" },
  { id: "160", text: "elephants return to the bones of their dead and touch them gently for a long time. If even elephants grieve, what does it say that we schedule grief for a long weekend?" },
  { id: "161", text: "cordyceps fungus can hijack an ant's brain and steer it to its death for the fungus's benefit. What's steering you right now that you've mistaken for your own desire?" },
  { id: "162", text: "Dunbar found humans can only really hold about 150 relationships; beyond that they're strangers with names. Of your hundreds of contacts, which 150 actually get you — and are you feeding them?" },
  { id: "163", text: "the Harvard study that tracked people for eighty years found one thing predicts a good life: the warmth of your relationships. Not the salary. So how's your actual portfolio doing?" },
  { id: "164", text: "the “Roseto effect” — a town that outlived its neighbors purely because everyone knew and looked after everyone. What would it cost you to build a little Roseto on your own street?" },
  { id: "165", text: "touch starvation is real; skin needs contact the way lungs need air. When were you last held long enough to actually exhale?" },
  { id: "166", text: "Frankl survived the camps and concluded a person can bear almost any how if they have a why. What's your why right now — and can you say it out loud without flinching?" },
  { id: "167", text: "Frankl named the “Sunday neurosis”: the quiet dread that surfaces when the busyness stops and you have to face the emptiness. What shows up in your silence, and what have you been using to keep it out?" },
  { id: "168", text: "Camus said we must imagine Sisyphus, forever rolling his rock, happy. What's your rock, and is there any world where you could push it with something like joy?" },
  { id: "169", text: "Kierkegaard called anxiety “the dizziness of freedom” — it spikes precisely because you could choose anything. What choice are you avoiding by staying overwhelmed?" },
  { id: "170", text: "Diogenes, asked by the most powerful man alive what he wanted, said only: stop blocking my sunlight. What would you ask the powerful to stop doing to your one small patch of light?" },
  { id: "171", text: "Epicurus said the recipe for happiness is modest — freedom, friends, and time to think, not more stuff. Which of those three are you actually starved of, under all the buying?" },
  { id: "172", text: "the paradox of choice: more options don't free us, they paralyze and then disappoint us. Where has “keeping your options open” actually kept you from choosing a life?" },
  { id: "173", text: "the McNamara fallacy: decide only by what you can measure, and soon you pretend the unmeasurable doesn't exist. What matters most in your life that would never show up on a dashboard?" },
  { id: "174", text: "Graeber argued half of us work jobs even we secretly believe are pointless. If yours vanished tomorrow and no one noticed, what would you actually want to have done with the years?" },
  { id: "175", text: "the man who invented the “like” button now keeps it off his own phone. What did you install that its own maker won't touch?" },
  { id: "176", text: "slot machines and your feed use the same trick: rewards that come at random, so you can never quite stop pulling. What are you pulling the lever on, hoping this refresh is the one?" },
  { id: "177", text: "Tricia Hersey preaches that rest is resistance and your worth was never your output. What would you do this weekend if you truly believed you'd already earned your rest by existing?" },
  { id: "178", text: "Parkinson's law: work expands to fill the time you give it. What would collapse into an afternoon if you stopped giving it your whole life?" },
  { id: "179", text: "institutions have a quiet habit of preserving the very problem they were built to solve, because the problem is the job. What problem in your life are you unconsciously keeping alive because you'd miss it?" },
  { id: "180", text: "the Luddites weren't anti-technology; they were workers smashing the machines that were stealing their livelihoods, and history smeared them for it. Whose fear of being made obsolete are you too quick to call irrational?" },
  { id: "181", text: "Frankl, Camus, Kierkegaard — every one of them says freedom is heavier than we admit. Where have you been begging to be told what to do just to put the weight down?" },
  { id: "182", text: "Rawls asked you to design a society as if you didn't know who you'd be born as. Would you accept your own life's luck if you'd drawn a different ticket?" },
  { id: "183", text: "Peter Singer asks why we'd ruin our shoes to save a drowning child in front of us but not lift a finger for one dying far away. Who's just far enough from you to be easy to forget?" },
  { id: "184", text: "the moral circle keeps widening — from tribe, to nation, to all people, maybe to all beings. Where does yours stop, honestly, and what's it costing whoever's just outside it?" },
  { id: "185", text: "Prometheus stole fire and got chained to a rock forever for the gift. What power have you reached for that came with a bill you're still paying?" },
  { id: "186", text: "Pandora opened the box and loosed every evil into the world, but one thing stayed behind: hope. If hope is what's left after everything's out — what's it asking you to do?" },
  { id: "187", text: "Nietzsche's cruelest test: if you had to live this exact life on infinite repeat, forever, would you cheer or scream? Which parts of today would you dread doing again?" },
  { id: "188", text: "Aristotle said happiness isn't a feeling but a practice — you get good at living by living well, like an instrument. What are you practicing every day without meaning to, and is it making you who you want to be?" },
  { id: "189", text: "the golden mean: courage sits between cowardice and recklessness, generosity between stinginess and waste. Which virtue have you overshot lately, mistaking too-much for good?" },
  { id: "190", text: "Taleb calls some things antifragile — they don't just survive stress, they need it to grow, like muscle or a forest. What in your life went soft precisely because you protected it too well?" },
  { id: "191", text: "via negativa: sometimes you improve a thing not by adding but by removing what's harming it. What could you subtract from your life this month that would quietly heal it?" },
  { id: "192", text: "the Lindy effect says the longer something has survived, the longer it's likely to last. What old, unfashionable practice have you dropped that had lasted a thousand years for a reason?" },
  { id: "193", text: "planetary boundaries mark nine limits we can't cross and stay safe; we've already blown past six. In your own life, which line have you crossed while telling yourself it's still fine?" },
  { id: "194", text: "Kate Raworth's doughnut says a good economy meets everyone's needs without blowing past the planet's means. What would your personal doughnut look like — the floor you won't drop below, the ceiling you won't exceed?" },
  { id: "195", text: "the Gaia hypothesis treats the whole living Earth as one self-regulating body that keeps itself habitable. If you're a cell in that body, is what you're doing today keeping the whole thing well, or feverish?" },
  { id: "196", text: "a tipping point is where a small last push flips a system into a new state it won't easily flip back from. What in your life is one small nudge away from a change you can't undo — for better or worse?" },
  { id: "197", text: "cradle-to-cradle design imagines products with no “away,” where every output feeds a new input. If your life left no waste, what would you have to stop throwing “away”?" },
  { id: "198", text: "termites build cathedrals with no architect, each one following a simple rule and leaving a trace for the next. What could your community build if everyone just did their small next piece and trusted the rest?" },
  { id: "199", text: "emergence is when simple parts following simple rules produce something none of them could plan — a flock, a market, a mind. What are you trying to control top-down that would work better if you tended the rules and let go?" },
  { id: "200", text: "fractals repeat the same shape at every scale — the branch echoes the tree echoes the forest. What pattern in your small daily life is quietly the same shape as your whole life?" },
  { id: "201", text: "the “edge of chaos” is where systems are most alive — not frozen in order, not lost in noise, but poised between. Are you currently too rigid or too scattered, and which way do you need to lean?" },
  { id: "202", text: "Frankl said between stimulus and response there's a space, and in that space is your freedom. How wide is your space today, and what keeps shrinking it to zero?" },
  { id: "203", text: "the marshmallow test was never really about willpower; the kids who trusted the adult would come back waited longer. What are you refusing to wait for simply because you've learned not to trust it'll come?" },
  { id: "204", text: "mirror neurons fire whether you do a thing or watch someone do it, so we literally feel each other. Whose stress have you caught this week like a cold, and whose calm could you catch instead?" },
  { id: "205", text: "the default mode network is the part of your brain that narrates “you” when you're doing nothing — and it's happiest ruminating. When your mind is idle, does it tell you a kind story or a cruel one?" },
  { id: "206", text: "flow states arrive when the challenge is just barely above your skill and self-consciousness vanishes. When did you last lose track of time in the good way — and why did you stop?" },
  { id: "207", text: "peacocks grow absurd, dangerous, useless tails purely because beauty, too, is a survival strategy. What have you pruned from your life as “impractical” that was actually keeping you alive?" },
  { id: "208", text: "animals play — they wrestle and chase for no reason but joy, and the ones who play are better at living. When did you last do something purely because it was fun, no outcome attached?" },
  { id: "209", text: "every night your brain runs impossible movies for free and calls them dreams. What is it trying to tell you that you're too busy in daylight to hear?" },
  { id: "210", text: "Csikszentmihalyi found people are often happiest working hard at something meaningful, and least happy “relaxing.” What hard thing have you been avoiding that might be where your joy is hiding?" },
  { id: "211", text: "Zuboff calls it surveillance capitalism: your inner life, mapped and sold to predict and nudge you. What did you decide today that you're sure was your own idea?" },
  { id: "212", text: "the firehose of falsehood doesn't want you to believe a lie — it wants you too tired to believe anything. What have you stopped caring about simply because caring got exhausting?" },
  { id: "213", text: "James Lovelock lived to 103 and kept changing his mind right to the end. When did you last let new evidence change something you'd built an identity on?" },
  { id: "214", text: "the Great Oxygenation, the asteroid, five mass extinctions — life has ended and begun again every time. What ending are you treating as final that might just be a beginning wearing a scary mask?" },
  { id: "215", text: "hysteresis: once a system flips, it won't flip back at the same point — the way out is longer than the way in. What did you slide into gradually that's turning out to be hard to climb back out of?" },
  { id: "216", text: "permafrost holds ancient carbon frozen for millennia, and it's starting to exhale. What have you kept frozen and safely buried that the current heat is bringing back up?" },
  { id: "217", text: "the honeybee tells the hive where the flowers are by dancing the angle to the sun on the comb wall. How well do you actually tell the people around you where you found something good?" },
  { id: "218", text: "an ant colony has no boss; order comes from millions of tiny signals left in the dirt. What are you waiting for a leader to fix that's actually made of a thousand small choices, including yours?" },
  { id: "219", text: "Sartre said we're condemned to be free — no script, no excuse, the authorship is yours. What are you blaming on circumstance that is, uncomfortably, a choice?" },
  { id: "220", text: "logotherapy says the will to meaning runs deeper than the will to pleasure or power. What have you been chasing pleasure or power to avoid admitting is really a hunger for meaning?" },
  { id: "221", text: "the expanding circle, the seven generations, the good ancestor — every wisdom keeps pointing the same way: care further out. Where does your caring run out of gas, and what would extend the range?" },
  { id: "222", text: "Nietzsche feared the “last man” — comfortable, incurious, blinking, who has invented happiness and risks nothing. How close to the last man did today bring you?" },
  { id: "223", text: "entropy guarantees everything drifts toward disorder; you're alive only because you keep spending energy to stay improbable. What in your life are you letting fall apart because you stopped feeding it?" },
  { id: "224", text: "the sun pours more energy on the Earth in an hour than humanity uses in a year, and mostly we don't look up. What abundance is pouring past you daily while you fixate on scarcity?" },
  { id: "225", text: "photosynthesis quietly performs the miracle we can't replicate — turning sunlight into food, in silence, everywhere, for free. What ordinary magic are you standing in that familiarity has made invisible?" },
  { id: "226", text: "blue-zone elders reach 100 not on kale alone but on purpose, community, and unhurried days. Which of those are you shortest on, and would more money actually fix it?" },
  { id: "227", text: "much of the nitrogen in your body was pulled from the air in a factory; you are, in part, an industrial product. What in you that feels natural was actually manufactured, and by whom?" },
  { id: "228", text: "cordyceps, the locust switch, the boiling frog — nature is full of things that change you without your consent. What's changing you right now, quietly, that you never agreed to?" },
  { id: "229", text: "Mauss studied the gift and found that to give, to receive, and to repay weaves the whole fabric of a society. Which of the three are you worst at — giving, receiving, or returning?" },
  { id: "230", text: "the potlatch honored the one who gave the most away, not the one who piled the most up. In a world that counts the opposite, what would you do if status came from generosity?" },
  { id: "231", text: "Aristotle said we are what we repeatedly do; excellence is a habit, not an act. What is today, repeated ten thousand times, quietly making you into?" },
  { id: "232", text: "Icarus didn't die from flying too high; the wax melted because he ignored the one warning that mattered. What thrilling thing are you doing while ignoring the one boring warning?" },
  { id: "233", text: "the phrase “rat race” is unfair to rats, who at least stop when they're full. When did you last recognize “full” and actually stop?" },
  { id: "234", text: "our word “economy” comes from the Greek for household management — the care of a home. When did managing the money stop feeling like caring for a home and start feeling like feeding a machine?" },
  { id: "235", text: "the drowning child you can see moves you instantly; a statistic never does. What suffering have you filed under “statistic” because the number was easier than the face?" },
  { id: "236", text: "a compass needle only works because it's free to swing; pin it down and it points nowhere true. What have you pinned down in yourself that's left you unable to tell which way is north?" },
  { id: "237", text: "a century of suppressing every small wildfire didn't prevent the big one; it just saved up the fuel for something worse. What conflict have you been suppressing that's only getting more flammable?" },
  { id: "238", text: "some octopus mothers guard their eggs until they starve; a few kinds of giving are total. Where is your giving generous, and where has it quietly become self-erasure?" },
  { id: "239", text: "a seed contains the whole tree and the patience to wait years for the right rain. What are you carrying, complete but dormant, waiting for conditions you keep trying to force?" },
  { id: "240", text: "the Greeks had two words for time: chronos, the ticking clock, and kairos, the ripe moment. Which have you been obeying, and when did you last catch a kairos before it passed?" },
  { id: "241", text: "Thoreau went to the woods to live deliberately, so he wouldn't reach the end and find he hadn't lived. If you did the math on your remaining Mondays, would today survive the audit?" },
  { id: "242", text: "a river never asks permission to change course; it just follows the lowest, truest path available. Where are you asking permission to become who you already are?" },
  { id: "243", text: "Lao Tzu said: when I let go of what I am, I become what I might be. What identity are you defending so hard that it's blocking the one trying to arrive?" },
  { id: "244", text: "the tyranny of the quantified self turns your walks, sleep, and breath into scores to beat. When did you last take a walk that wasn't also a data point?" },
  { id: "245", text: "mycorrhizal networks reroute nutrients around a damaged tree to keep it alive while it heals. Who's rerouting support to you right now that you've been too proud to notice?" },
  { id: "246", text: "the “Anthropocene” names an age where one species became a geological force without ever meaning to. What are you changing at scale, by accident, just by living the way everyone lives?" },
  { id: "247", text: "wolves, otters, beavers — remove the predator and the whole system swells and then starves. What did you remove from your life for comfort that was actually keeping you in balance?" },
  { id: "248", text: "Kropotkin, Margulis, Simard — the science keeps quietly overturning the story that life is mainly a fight. If cooperation is actually the headline, what have you been bracing against for no reason?" },
  { id: "249", text: "four-day-week trials keep finding people get the same done and are far happier. What are you convinced requires all your hours that secretly doesn't?" },
  { id: "250", text: "Kimmerer says gratitude is a subversive act in a culture built on manufactured wanting. What are you numb with abundance toward that would stun someone who had none of it?" },
  { id: "251", text: "a candle gives all its light by spending itself; there's no version where it shines and stays whole. What are you unwilling to spend, and is it the very thing meant to be burned?" },
  { id: "252", text: "the Sabbath, the fallow field, the winter, the exhale — every living system has a built-in stop. Where's yours, and when did you last honor it without guilt?" },
  { id: "253", text: "a murmuration has no leader and never crashes; a traffic jam has thousands of leaders and barely moves. What are you over-managing that would flow better if you trusted the simple rule?" },
  { id: "254", text: "lichens are the first life to colonize bare rock, dissolving stone into the first soil for everyone after. What thankless, foundational thing are you doing that others will build on and forget?" },
  { id: "255", text: "the tragedy isn't that the commons fails — it's that we forgot we ever knew how to share one. What did your grandparents know about enough that you're having to relearn from a book?" },
  { id: "256", text: "Frankl noticed the ones who survived weren't the strongest but the ones who kept a reason to live. What's your reason, stripped of everything comfortable — is it still there?" },
  { id: "257", text: "a forest doesn't hurry and nothing is left undone; growth and rest turn out to be the same wisdom seen twice. Where does your hurry actually leave things undone that slowness would finish?" },
  { id: "258", text: "we spend the first half of life accumulating and are often startled that the second half is about letting go. What are you gripping now that you already sense you'll one day have to open your hand around?" },
  { id: "259", text: "bees will work themselves to death for a hive they'll never see finished; devotion doesn't need to see the end. What are you devoted to beyond your own lifespan, if anything?" },
  { id: "260", text: "the overview effect astronauts describe is really just paying full attention to something they'd taken for granted. What in your ordinary life would look miraculous if you saw it from far enough away?" },
  { id: "261", text: "Aldo Leopold said we abuse land because we see it as a commodity we own, not a community we belong to. What would you stop doing the moment you felt you belonged to a place instead of owning it?" },
  { id: "262", text: "a beaver's “mistake” — flooding the land — turns out to make the most fertile habitat around. What have you been calling a mess that might be building something you can't see yet?" },
  { id: "263", text: "Rachel Carson wrote that those who contemplate the beauty of the earth find reserves of strength that last as long as life. When did you last refill from that particular well?" },
  { id: "264", text: "deep time makes a human life a single blink, which is either terrifying or wildly freeing. Which does it feel like to you today, and what does that reveal?" },
  { id: "265", text: "Wendell Berry farmed one small place for decades and found a whole universe in fidelity to a single patch of ground. What would deepen if you stopped looking for somewhere better and committed to here?" },
  { id: "266", text: "a wound heals from the edges in and from the bottom up, on its own schedule, not yours. What are you picking at because it's not healing as fast as you demanded?" },
  { id: "267", text: "the “hungry ghost” of Buddhist lore has a huge belly and a pinhole mouth — endlessly craving, never fed. Which of your appetites has a mouth too small to ever be satisfied?" },
  { id: "268", text: "redwood seeds are among the tiniest, and they make the tallest living things on Earth. What small thing are you dismissing because you can't yet see what it's the seed of?" },
  { id: "269", text: "Ostrom, Kropotkin, the commons — cooperation isn't naive; it's often the shrewdest long game there is. Where has your cynicism been quietly more expensive than trust would have been?" },
  { id: "270", text: "the moon doesn't compete with the sun; it just shows up faithfully at its own hour. Whose light are you dimming yourself trying to outshine, when your hour is simply different?" },
  { id: "271", text: "a scar is just skin that decided living was worth a mark. Which of yours have you been ashamed of that's really a receipt for survival?" },
  { id: "272", text: "the tragedy of the commons has a twin nobody names: the comedy of the commons, where sharing makes everyone richer. Where in your life is sharing quietly the more selfish-smart move?" },
  { id: "273", text: "nearly every cell in your body gets replaced within about seven years; the you of a decade ago is literally gone. So what are you still carrying from that vanished person that you could set down?" },
  { id: "274", text: "Frankl, the Stoics, the Buddha — three different centuries, one message: you can't always choose the wave, only the surfing. What wave are you exhausting yourself trying to stop instead of ride?" },
  { id: "275", text: "permaculture's first principle is “observe and interact” — sit with a place a full year before you change it. What are you rushing to fix that you haven't yet sat with long enough to understand?" },
  { id: "276", text: "the butterfly effect means a tiny act can cascade into something vast and unpredictable. Which small kindness or cruelty of yours might be echoing somewhere you'll never see?" },
  { id: "277", text: "a chrysalis isn't a cozy sleeping bag; inside, the caterpillar dissolves into goo before it becomes a wing. What if the falling-apart you're in isn't the failure but the transformation?" },
  { id: "278", text: "we protect children from all discomfort and then wonder why they're fragile; the tree grown in a dome has weak wood. Where has comfort quietly made you brittle?" },
  { id: "279", text: "the Iroquois Thanksgiving Address greets the water, the trees, the winds, and the stars — a full hour of noticing before any business. What would change if you began each day by thanking what keeps you alive?" },
  { id: "280", text: "Simone Weil said attention, absolute unmixed attention, is prayer. Who or what got your undivided attention today, and who got only your leftovers?" },
  { id: "281", text: "a forest fire clears the canopy so light can finally reach the seedlings that waited in the dark. What loss in your life quietly let something long-suppressed finally grow?" },
  { id: "282", text: "the paradox of the age: more comfort than any humans ever had, and a strange, gnawing sense that something's missing. What's the shape of your particular missing thing?" },
  { id: "283", text: "octopuses, crows, cephalopods — intelligence evolved many separate times, in wildly different bodies. What if your way of being smart isn't the only kind, or even the best kind, in the room?" },
  { id: "284", text: "Gandhi called it one of the seven social sins: commerce without morality, science without humanity, knowledge without character. Which of those have you made peace with because everyone else has?" },
  { id: "285", text: "the deepest roots grow in the hardest seasons, when the plant can't grow up so it grows down. What did your worst year build in you underground that your best years now stand on?" },
  { id: "286", text: "a river delta is where the water finally slows, spreads, and becomes the most fertile land there is. What would get fertile in your life if you let it slow down and spread out?" },
  { id: "287", text: "Thoreau said the price of anything is the amount of life you exchange for it. What did you buy recently, and how many hours of your one life did it actually cost?" },
  { id: "288", text: "the wisest cultures treat elders and children as the two most sacred ends of the same thread. Which end have you drifted from, and what are you missing because of it?" },
  { id: "289", text: "cells that refuse to die when they should are what we call cancer; even at the cellular level, endings are a kindness. What in your life needs permission to end so the rest can stay healthy?" },
  { id: "290", text: "the North Star doesn't move; it's the fixed point that lets everything else be navigated. What's your fixed point — and if you can't name it fast, is that the real problem?" },
  { id: "291", text: "every language on Earth has a word for “home” and none of them simply mean “house.” What makes a place home for you, and are you actually building any of it?" },
  { id: "292", text: "kintsugi, the scar, the nurse log, the compost — the whole living world insists brokenness is where new life enters. Where have you been fighting to stay unbroken at the cost of staying unchanged?" },
  { id: "293", text: "Aesop's ant stored food while the grasshopper sang, but a life that's all storage and no song isn't much of a life either. Which one have you overcorrected into lately?" },
  { id: "294", text: "the vagus nerve means a slow exhale can physically talk your body out of panic; calm is partly a skill, not a mood. When it all felt like too much today, did you remember you had a lever?" },
  { id: "295", text: "we're the only animal that can picture a future so vividly we grieve and dread things that haven't happened. That's a superpower and a curse — which unreal future are you living in right now?" },
  { id: "296", text: "one keystone habit, like a daily walk, can quietly reorganize a whole life around it. What tiny keystone could you set down today and let the rest rearrange?" },
  { id: "297", text: "the ancient practice of pilgrimage worked because the long walk changed the walker, not the destination. What in your life would be solved less by arriving and more by the walking?" },
  { id: "298", text: "Lao Tzu said a journey of a thousand miles begins beneath your feet — not with a plan, with a step. What thousand-mile thing have you been planning instead of starting?" },
  { id: "299", text: "the last line of nearly every wisdom tradition rhymes: pay attention, give thanks, let go, be kind, come home. Which of those five is your soul most behind on right now?" },
  { id: "300", text: "after all of this — the fungi, the wolves, the stars, the saints, the slow exhale — the only real question left is the first one. What do you, specifically, want to do with the fact that you're alive right now?" },
];

